commitResults.messageBody:
Update the aforementioned files to better reflect on the current
project. Any mentioned of "Duke" was changed to "FunBox".

FunBoxGear.java contains the functionalities which will be used by
FunBox.

It contains basic commands such as,

* Greet
* Echo
* Exit

Update FunBoxGear.java with functionalities to store user's messages
and display these messages in a list.

Subsequently, FunBox.java is updated to use the new functionalities
implemented.
Add Task.java for better encapsulation under OOP principles.

Update Task.java to reflect that the code was reused with
modifications.

Update FunBoxGear.java to follow closely to the OOP principle.

Functions such as isBye, isList etc. used to detect the type of
message sent by the users has similar behaviour resulting in code
duplication.

The getCommands() function remove such duplication by combining the
aforementioned functions together.

FunBoxGear.java has also been updated to make use of Task.java.

Update FunBox.java to utilize the updated FunBoxGear.java. Multiple
if-else statements has been reduced to a single if statements.

Deadline, Event, ToDo are different type of tasks with some
similarity between them.

Due to the similarity, they all inherit from Task.java. Inheritance
is used to follow the OOP principle: polymorphism.

Update FunBoxGear.java to make use of the newly added files:

* Deadline.java
* Event.java
* Task.java

This allows users to categorize the different type of tasks.
Removed emoji due unmappable character error when running test.

Update EXPECTED.TXT and input.txt such that the current input and
result can be used as a benchmark to compare to when the code
changes in the future.

Add FunBoxExceptions.java to add error handlings for FunBox.

Adding custom exceptions allows for handling of specific exceptions
related to FunBox

Update FunBoxGear.java to utilize FunBoxExceptions' functionalities
for error handling.
Update FunBoxGear.java to allow users to delete tasks they inputted.

Update FunBoxGear.java to include exceptions for mark, unmark, and
delete functions.

This is to provide a more comprehensive error handling such that
users would understand where their command entered went wrong.
